## These are opinions, not a standard

Unlike a plugin adapted from a published specification, this one does **not**
encode an external standard, and there is no "correct" body of rules it deviates
from. The go-ddd project is one experienced practitioner's **defensible set of
choices** for building Go backends with real business rules — and it says so
itself (the source's FAQ is candid about when DDD is overkill, what it
deliberately omits, and where it would decide differently).

This plugin keeps that spirit. Treat its guidance as a coherent, opinionated
house style to adopt wholesale or adapt, not as universal law. Notable choices
that are deliberate and reasonable people reverse:

- **`Id`, not `ID`** — house style, enforced on purpose (the corresponding
  linter rules are disabled deliberately in the source). Pick one and apply it
  everywhere.
- **sqlc over an ORM** — chosen so the row-to-aggregate mapping stays explicit
  and reviewable. Nothing in the architecture requires it; the repository
  interfaces don't know it exists.
- **Onion / DDD layering, one bounded context, one deployable** — the honest
  starting point for most services, not a mandate to build microservices.
- **Money as integer minor units, currency attached** — the one choice this
  guidance treats as close to non-negotiable for anything touching prices.

Where a skill states a rule, it also tries to state *why*, so you can judge
whether the reason applies to your project.

